My-gather is a Go CLI tool that reads pt-stalk output directories and
produces self-contained HTML diagnostic reports for MySQL/Percona support
engineers and DBAs.

Non-negotiable principles:

1. Single static binary. The tool ships as one statically-linked executable
   with no runtime dependencies. A support engineer must be able to scp it
   to a customer jump host and run it with no install, no interpreter, no
   libc version negotiation. Cross-compile for linux/amd64, linux/arm64,
   darwin/amd64, darwin/arm64 at minimum.

2. Read-only on inputs. Never modify, move, or delete anything under the
   pt-stalk output directory.

3. Degrade gracefully. Real-world pt-stalk collections are often incomplete,
   truncated, or have missing files. The tool must produce a useful report
   from whatever is present and clearly mark what is missing — never panic,
   never silently drop data. Parser errors are captured in the report, not
   propagated as fatal.

4. Deterministic output. Same input directory must always produce
   byte-identical HTML (modulo timestamps explicitly rendered in the report).
   Map iteration, goroutine ordering, and floating-point formatting must not
   leak into output.

5. Self-contained HTML. The report is one file with all CSS, JS, fonts, and
   data embedded. Chart library JS is bundled into the binary via `go:embed`
   and inlined into the report at generation time. No CDN fetches at
   view-time — reports must render offline from an air-gapped laptop.

6. Library-first. The CLI (package main) is a thin wrapper around packages
   that are importable independently: `parse/` for pt-stalk file parsers,
   `model/` for the typed in-memory representation, `render/` for HTML
   generation. Every exported function has a stable godoc contract.

7. Typed errors, not strings. Use sentinel errors and typed error structs
   (`var ErrNotAPtStalkDir = errors.New(...)`, `type ParseError struct{...}`)
   so callers can `errors.Is` / `errors.As`. No `fmt.Errorf` for conditions
   a caller needs to branch on.

8. Every parser has a reference fixture. For each pt-stalk collector we
   support, there must be at least one fixture file under `testdata/` and a
   round-trip test using `golden` files. Fixture data comes from the real
   examples under references/examples/.

9. Zero network at runtime. No phoning home, no telemetry, no update checks.

10. Minimal dependencies. Prefer the standard library. Any third-party
    module must be justified in the plan. No framework imports for problems
    the stdlib handles (flag parsing, HTML templating, JSON, time).

11. Reports are for humans under pressure. Prioritize the 80% signal — what
    triggered the collection, what the system looked like at trigger time,
    what changed — over exhaustive metric dumps.

12. Go version pinned. Target the current Go stable release; pin in go.mod
    and CI. No build tags that diverge behavior between platforms except
    where truly necessary (e.g., path separators are handled via filepath).